<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-07-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-07-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="301" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d301">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                        <persName type="to">Wu Ting-fang</persName>.</hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-07-18"><hi rend="italic">July 18,
                                        1900</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr.</hi> Wu: In reference to your inquiry
                                made this morning on behalf of the Grand Secretary Li Hung Chang, I
                                have the honor to reply that the position and the intention of the
                                United States Government in favor of the territorial and
                                administrative integrity of China are set forth with sufficient
                                clearness in our circular of the 3d of July,<note n="1" xml:id="d301fn1">See <ref target="#pg_299">p. 299</ref>.</note>
                                that we still hold the same attitude, and that we have ground to
                                believe that similar views are entertained by all the other
                                powers.</p>
                            <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay</hi>.</signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>